Now that I know myself better it just makes me incredibly sad. Idk. I'm tired.

It puts such a clear lens on behaviors I had before, on my interactions and it forced me to learn things the hard way. People I hurt, people who most likely stopped talking to me for either not being present enough or too present. For having such sharp and oscillating emotions.
Last few days have been tough and I've been ruminating a lot and I can't help but wonder how my relationships, romantic and friendly, would have ended up if I had caught my ADHD early...

And ofc it isn't easy, even just starting is never easy, but dammit you can at least say you tried. That you are *trying*.

Just liking all the relatable anxiety and depression memes won't help, trust me. I've tried. If you know it's a problem that's effecting your health, your relationships and your quality of life, acknowledge it and work on it. Little by little.

OBVIOUSLY certain things are circumstantial but you should at least want better for yourself. Speaking as someone who's mentally ill and has been through and is STILL going through it like. I got fucking tired, I'm still working on it, I will never *stop* working on it.

I'm tired of hearing people casually talk about their unhealthy behaviors in life as if they've just given up on making themselves better. Yes it takes time and work, it takes lots of self reflection and keeping track but ffs it's better than just accepting it.
At some point you can't be content with being unhealthy.
